## Opening narrative for Findings section

The documentation reviewed demonstrates that CCBNY has meaningful AML, sanctions, data governance, model governance, and change-management frameworks in place. However, for a DFS 504 data lineage assessment, the primary issue is not the absence of policies or governance structures; it is the absence of a fully integrated, evidence-backed lineage framework that proves data feeding transaction monitoring and filtering systems is complete, accurate, traceable, controlled, and certification-ready. DFS 504.3 requires transaction monitoring and filtering programs to include governance, data mapping, model validation, data input and program output testing, documentation of assumptions and thresholds, data source identification, validation of data integrity/accuracy/quality, extraction/loading controls, vendor governance, qualified personnel, and documented remediation for areas requiring improvement. ([Legal Information Institute][1])

